The Familiar Aspect of New Antisemitism
Why do many Holocaust survivors feel emerging threats to Judaism before they become apparent to everyone?
Because they know that supposedly "harmless" hints can turn into accusations and ultimately lead to discrimination that is then legally anchored.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what's at play.
That way, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so we can survive as well.
Since the first round of the presidential elections in France, it is clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean-Marie Le Pen or other uncouth right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often times opportunists of fascism or communism without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people - with the "educated bourgeoisie" in connection with mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often reminds us of that of the opportunists of this antidemocratic movement.
This is not the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, thank goodness - but it is the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to Great Britain should be mentioned: recently, he entitled Israel as "this damned little country" during a dinner party in London.
His vulgar expression is not particularly frightening.
What's frightening is the reaction to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the Blair government demand his recall. The matter was dealt with in the public as just another scandal.
The French press presented the ambassador seriously as a victim of British small fry gossip and not of his own deplorable attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to Great Britain has many allies among Europe's elite.
Ambassador Bernard however did us a service: through him it became clear how widespread these new anti-Semitic resentments are.
As a columnist put it so aptly: Israel became an object of hatred, whose name is not to be uttered out loud.
We, however, are not only forced to dare, we are even obliged to express it.
In the face of daily attacks on Jews and synagogues in France, we may not remain silent.
It's a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without having to worry about their safety.
Antisemitic incidents are also reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, Holland, and in parts of Eastern Europe.
We may not remain silent about the fact that the denial of the Holocaust is becoming everyday. Nor may we remain silent about the comparisons that antisemites and antizionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers in a Palestinian television broadcast, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we must "confront the new Nazi plague emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It's not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. One almost hates them everywhere".
During the television broadcast of a Friday prayer in Palestinian television, the preacher called on the Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. Kill them and those Americans who are just like them wherever you are."
What we should think about in the context of antisemitism is that it always starts with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If Jew hatred is not curbed, it usually leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and eventually undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The struggle against antisemitism is therefore a task for both Jews and non-Jews.
At the moment, the points of attack in this struggle are less clear than ever before, because an extraordinary aspect of today's antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism remains always the same - namely to attack Jews - it nevertheless changes its face, its strategy, its rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
Once the Jewish religion was the target.
When this did not give in, the Jews were expelled or killed.
When in the 19th century the theory of race cast its spell on people, Jews were attacked because of their belonging to a bad race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today defamed as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just as with other nations, it is perfectly legitimate to take a critical stance against certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
However, Antizionism is constantly becoming more similar to Antisemitism.
Antizionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I'm only against the existence of Great Britain, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
You wouldn't believe them.
It's difficult to love or respect a people, but hate their state.
And yet, there are people in connection with Israel who claim to be able to do just that.
Israel-bashing is on the agenda in various UN organizations.
This demonization of the only democratic state in the Middle East is a core point of this new antisemitism.
If Israel is described as "the enemy of all that is good and the source of all evil", then the "doctrine of contempt" is circulating within the UN, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament, puts it.
This constant presentation of a nation as an enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people.
So liegen den zahlreichen anti-jüdischen Übergriffen in vielen Ländern die Verteufelungen Israels zugrunde, die sich einer antisemitischen Terminologie bedienen.
Attacken auf Synagogen werden oftmals durch die Verwendung dieser verleumderischen Sprache im Zusammenhang mit dem Nahen Osten ausgelöst.
Im Vergleich zu früheren anti-jüdischen Ausbrüchen, handelt es sich bei dem heutigen Antisemitismus weniger um Angriffe auf einzelne Juden, als vielmehr um eine Attacke gegen den "kollektiven Juden", also gegen den Staat Israel.
Derartige Attacken haben aber eine Kettenreaktion von Übergriffen auf einzelne Juden und jüdische Institutionen in ganz Europa und Lateinamerika in Gang gesetzt.
Früher waren die gefährlichsten Antisemiten diejenigen, die die Welt judenrein machen wollten.
The most dangerous antisemites of today are those who want to make the world judenstaatrein.
